"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 7–9
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-7-9.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing data; merge_comm skips present entries)

Key Christological decisions:
- The Flood narrative: the primary NT Christological reading is 1 Pet 3:20-21 (ark/water as
  type of baptism) and Matt 24:37-39 (the days of Noah as eschatological type for the coming
  of the Son of Man). These are explicit NT typological readings; all other connections are
  secondary and noted with appropriate directness levels.
- 8:4 Ark resting on the 17th of the 7th month: corresponds to the 17th of Nisan in the
  post-Exodus calendar (3 days after Passover), the date of Christ's resurrection. This
  coincidence is noted as a canonical pattern rather than asserted as intentional by the author.
- 8:7-11 Raven and dove: the dove's connection to the Spirit at Christ's baptism (Matt 3:16)
  is strong thematic material; the raven is not given a direct Christological reading.
- 8:20-21 Burnt offerings and pleasing aroma: Eph 5:2 directly applies the pleasing-aroma
  language to Christ's sacrifice; this is a clear NT warrant for typological connection.
- 9:4 Blood prohibition: the sanctity of blood prepares the covenant theology of blood
  atonement that culminates in Christ; noted as a canonical trajectory, not a direct type.
- 9:6 Image of God as basis of accountability: Christ as the perfect image-bearer (Col 1:15)
  whose blood was unjustly shed creates the supreme irony the NT develops.
- 9:13 Rainbow in Rev 4:3 and 10:1: strong canonical connection; the Noahic covenant sign
  appears around the divine throne and the exalted Christ in Revelation.
- 9:25-27 Curses and blessings: Christ becomes a curse (Gal 3:13); Shem's line carries
  Christ's genealogy; Japheth's inclusion anticipates Gentile incorporation (Rom 11).
- Noah as second Adam who falls: the flood does not solve human sin; only Christ, the last
  Adam (1 Cor 15:45), breaks the pattern both Adams failed to overcome.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"7": {
"1": "<p>The LORD's declaration &#8212; &#8220;I have found you righteous in this generation&#8221; &#8212; grounds Noah's deliverance in righteousness, not merit alone but covenant standing. The NT uses Noah's righteousness as a type: Heb 11:7 says Noah, &#8220;in holy fear built an ark to save his family. By his faith he condemned the world and became heir of the righteousness that is in keeping with faith.&#8221; Christ is the one in whom true righteousness is established (2 Cor 5:21: &#8220;God made him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&#8221;). The deliverance of the righteous man through judgment is the structural template for Christ's role as the righteous one who brings many through judgment to life.</p>",
"2": "<p>The distinction between clean and unclean animals anticipates the entire Mosaic purity system. Christ's declaration that &#8220;nothing that enters a person from the outside can defile them&#8221; (Mark 7:15, 18&#8211;19: &#8220;in saying this, Jesus declared all foods clean&#8221;) abrogates the clean/unclean food distinctions. Peter's vision at Joppa (Acts 10:10&#8211;16) extends this to Gentiles: what God has declared clean must not be called unclean. The clean/unclean framework that begins here runs through the entire OT covenant system and is dissolved in Christ, who fulfills and surpasses the purity it represented.</p>",
"3": "<p>Seven pairs of birds were preserved to keep &#8220;their various kinds alive throughout the earth.&#8221; The preservation of life through the ark points toward Christ's role as the preserver of life through his own body. Jesus applies the bird imagery to divine providence directly: &#8220;Are not two sparrows sold for a penny? Yet not one of them will fall to the ground outside your Father's care&#8221; (Matt 10:29). The comprehensive preservation of created kinds in the ark is a shadow of the comprehensive renewal of all creation that Christ will accomplish (Rom 8:21; Rev 21:5).</p>",
"4": "<p>The forty days of rain connect the Flood to the forty-day pattern that runs through the redemptive narrative: Moses on Sinai (Exod 24:18), Elijah's journey to Horeb (1 Kgs 19:8), and most directly, Jesus's forty days of temptation in the wilderness (Matt 4:1&#8211;2). Just as the Flood's forty days tested and purified the earth, Christ's forty days in the wilderness recapitulated Israel's forty years in the wilderness — but where Israel and Adam failed, Christ succeeded. The forty-day framework is a pattern of testing preceding commissioning that culminates in the Son who passes the test.</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;Noah did all that the LORD commanded him&#8221; &#8212; the obedience formula appears repeatedly in Genesis 6&#8211;9 as the narrative's moral anchor. Noah's complete obedience is a type of Christ's perfect obedience, but where Noah is righteous, Christ is the source of righteousness. Paul contrasts the first Adam's disobedience with Christ's obedience: &#8220;Through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous&#8221; (Rom 5:19). Christ's obedience is not comparative but constitutive: it is the ground on which sinners are declared righteous. Noah's faithful compliance points toward the one whose obedience was &#8220;even to death&#8212;even death on a cross&#8221; (Phil 2:8).</p>",
"6": "<p>Noah was six hundred years old when the floodwaters came &#8212; a chronological marker situating the Flood in the antediluvian genealogical sequence. Christ enters the world through this post-Flood lineage; Luke 3:36 includes Noah in the genealogy of Jesus (Noah &#8594; Shem &#8594; ... &#8594; Abraham &#8594; David &#8594; Jesus). This verse does not carry direct Christological freight but situates the Flood within the genealogical trajectory that culminates in the incarnation.</p>",
"7": "<p>Noah and his household entered the ark to escape the floodwaters &#8212; the type that 1 Pet 3:20&#8211;21 explicitly invokes: &#8220;a few people, eight in all, were saved through water, and this water symbolizes baptism that now saves you also.&#8221; The ark is the vehicle of salvation through judgment: those inside are preserved while the waters of judgment cover everything outside. As a type, the ark points toward Christ, in whom believers are sheltered from the wrath of God (Rom 8:1: &#8220;no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus&#8221;). The eight persons saved through water become the NT's paradigm for baptismal salvation through the death and resurrection of Christ.</p>",
"8": "<p>Clean and unclean animals entered the ark in pairs &#8212; see v2 on the clean/unclean distinction that Christ dissolves. Here the point is comprehensive preservation: both categories of animals were saved within the ark regardless of their ritual status. Christ similarly draws all kinds of people to himself without distinction: &#8220;There is neither Jew nor Gentile, neither slave nor free, nor is there male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus&#8221; (Gal 3:28). The ark's comprehensiveness anticipates the church's inclusivity.</p>",
"9": "<p>The animals came to Noah and entered the ark as God commanded &#8212; the gathering of all kinds to the place of safety. Jesus applies the gathering motif to his own mission: &#8220;When I am lifted up from the earth, I will draw all people to myself&#8221; (John 12:32). Isaiah's vision of the nations gathering to the LORD's mountain (Isa 2:2&#8211;3) and the Great Commission's gathering of all nations (Matt 28:19) extend the pattern: as creation's representatives were drawn to the ark, all nations are drawn to Christ. The verb &#8220;came&#8221; &#8212; they came without being driven &#8212; suggests the voluntary gathering that Christ's exaltation produces.</p>",
"10": "<p>After seven days the floodwaters came &#8212; the completed week before judgment arrives. The seven-day wait echoes the creation week and the seven-day Passover unleavened bread festival; it anticipates the theological weight of the seventh day as completion. The Flood judgment that arrives after seven days is a type of the final judgment that arrives after the fullness of time: Jesus consistently frames the coming of the Son of Man as arriving after periods of waiting and readiness (Matt 24:42&#8211;44; 25:1&#8211;13). The seven-day completion pattern is the template for understanding sacred time that culminates in Christ's ushering in of the last day.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;All the springs of the great deep burst forth, and the floodgates of the heavens were opened&#8221; &#8212; the cosmic undoing of the separations God made on the second and third days of creation (Gen 1:6&#8211;9). The reversal of creation order in the Flood anticipates the cosmic disruptions that attend Christ's death: darkness for three hours (Matt 27:45), the temple veil torn (Matt 27:51), earthquake and the opening of tombs (Matt 27:51&#8211;52). Both events involve cosmic disruption accompanying divine judgment. The de-creation of the Flood gives way to re-creation; Christ's death gives way to resurrection and the beginning of new creation (2 Cor 5:17).</p>",
"12": "<p>Rain fell on the earth for forty days and forty nights &#8212; see v4 on the forty-day pattern. The sustained duration of the judgment &#8212; not a brief storm but forty days of unrelenting divine action &#8212; is the framework within which the ark's preservation is understood. The thoroughness of the judgment is what makes the salvation significant: it is not a partial danger but total cosmic judgment from which the ark alone provides refuge. The thoroughness of sin's judgment that Christ absorbs on the cross is what makes atonement complete: he experiences not partial but full divine wrath on behalf of sinners.</p>",
"13": "<p>On the very day Noah and his family entered the ark &#8212; the precision of the divine timing. Noah's entry into the ark is on a specific historical day that the narrator records; the Flood is a historical event, not a myth. The NT insists on the same historical specificity for Christ: &#8220;under Pontius Pilate&#8221; (1 Tim 6:13; the creed). The Flood as a historical judgment is the framework for understanding the cross as a historical atonement. Jesus himself appeals to Noah's historical reality as the warrant for the eschatological judgment he announces (Matt 24:37&#8211;39).</p>",
"14": "<p>Every kind of creature entered the ark &#8212; the comprehensive preservation of created life. This breadth anticipates Paul's vision in Rom 8:21 of &#8220;the creation itself&#8221; being &#8220;liberated from its bondage to decay and brought into the freedom and glory of the children of God.&#8221; The ark's preservation of every kind points toward the new creation's comprehensive restoration that Christ inaugurates: not just human souls but the whole created order redeemed and renewed (Rev 21:5: &#8220;I am making everything new&#8221;).</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;Pairs of all creatures that have the breath of life in them came to Noah and entered the ark&#8221; &#8212; the &#8220;breath of life&#8221; (<em>nishmat chayyim</em>) connects to Gen 2:7, where God breathes the breath of life into Adam. The preserved breath-of-life creatures are the remnant of the creation God breathed into existence. Christ is the life-giver who renews the breath of life: John 20:22 records Jesus breathing on the disciples and saying &#8220;Receive the Holy Spirit&#8221; &#8212; an explicit echo of Gen 2:7, signaling the new creation. The creatures preserved by their breath-of-life receive renewed breath-of-life through the risen Christ.</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;The LORD shut him in&#8221; &#8212; the divine sealing of the ark is one of the most significant phrases in the Flood narrative. God himself closes the door, sealing those inside in safety. Jesus applies the door imagery to himself: &#8220;I am the door; if anyone enters through me, he will be saved&#8221; (John 10:9). Those whom God seals in Christ are secured by divine action, not human effort: &#8220;God's solid foundation stands firm, sealed with this inscription: The Lord knows those who are his&#8221; (2 Tim 2:19). The LORD's shutting of the ark is the type of the divine securing of believers in Christ, against whom no judgment can prevail (John 10:28&#8211;29).</p>",
"17": "<p>The flood kept coming for forty days, and as the waters increased they lifted the ark &#8212; the ark rises above the waters of judgment rather than being submerged by them. This is the typological core: those inside the ark are elevated by the very judgment that destroys everything outside. Paul uses the same logic for baptism: &#8220;We were therefore buried with him through baptism into death in order that, just as Christ was raised from the dead through the glory of the Father, we too may live a new life&#8221; (Rom 6:4). The believer goes through the water of judgment in Christ and rises on the other side to new life. The ark literally floats above destruction; believers are metaphorically above condemnation (Rom 8:1).</p>",
"18": "<p>The waters rose and increased greatly, and the ark floated on the surface &#8212; the ark sustained above the waters throughout the flood. The imagery of being sustained above the waters of death connects to Christ's power over death. Job longs for one who will plead his case before God and &#8220;redeem me from the hand of the mighty&#8221; (Job 5:15); the psalmists cry to be saved from the &#8220;deep waters&#8221; (Ps 69:1&#8211;2, 14&#8211;15) and from being &#8220;overwhelmed by the flood waters&#8221; (Ps 124:4). Christ answers these cries by walking on the water (Matt 14:25) and calming the storm (Mark 4:39), revealing himself as the one who sustains his people above the waters of judgment and death.</p>",
"19": "<p>All the high mountains under the entire heavens were covered &#8212; the totality of the judgment, with no mountain of refuge anywhere on earth. The only refuge was the ark. The NT applies the same logic to salvation through Christ: &#8220;Salvation is found in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given to mankind by which we must be saved&#8221; (Acts 4:12). As no mountain stood above the floodwaters, no human achievement or religious alternative stands above the judgment of sin. The comprehensiveness of the judgment is what makes the particularity of the ark &#8212; and of Christ &#8212; non-negotiable rather than narrow.</p>",
"20": "<p>The waters rose more than fifteen cubits above the mountains &#8212; an additional depth above the mountain peaks, ensuring that no escape was possible outside the ark. The excess of the flood above the highest human refuge reinforces the theological point of v19: the judgment is thorough and complete. Christ's atonement is similarly complete: &#8220;he is able to save completely those who come to God through him&#8221; (Heb 7:25). The flood's comprehensiveness is matched by the completeness of Christ's salvation, which exceeds every human spiritual mountain.</p>",
"21": "<p>Every living thing that moved on land perished &#8212; the universal scope of the judgment. Paul applies the same universality to sin's consequences: &#8220;For the wages of sin is death&#8221; (Rom 6:23); &#8220;death came to all people, because all sinned&#8221; (Rom 5:12). The Flood's universal judgment on the living is the type of the universal spiritual death that sin has brought. Against this universal death stands the universal life-offer of Christ: &#8220;For as in Adam all die, so in Christ all will be made alive&#8221; (1 Cor 15:22). The scope of the judgment matches the scope of the salvation.</p>",
"22": "<p>Everything with the breath of life in its nostrils died &#8212; the breath of life (see v15) extinguished universally outside the ark. The death of all breath-of-life creatures outside the ark is the type of spiritual death outside of Christ. Christ as the one who gives the Spirit (John 20:22; Acts 2:33) restores the breath of life to those who were spiritually dead. Paul describes the unregenerate as &#8220;dead in your transgressions and sins&#8221; (Eph 2:1) and the regenerate as made alive by God's Spirit &#8212; the same life-giving Spirit who hovered over the chaotic waters of creation (Gen 1:2) and descended on Christ at his baptism (Matt 3:16).</p>",
"23": "<p>&#8220;Only Noah was left, and those with him in the ark&#8221; &#8212; the remnant saved through judgment. The remnant theme is one of the most persistent in the OT: Isaiah (10:20&#8211;22), Micah (5:7&#8211;8), Zephaniah (3:12&#8211;13), and Ezra all develop the idea of a surviving remnant through which God fulfills his covenant purposes. Paul applies it to the Gentile mission: &#8220;Though the number of the Israelites be like the sand by the sea, only the remnant will be saved&#8221; (Rom 9:27). The remnant preserved in the ark is the prototype of all subsequent remnant theology, culminating in those whom God preserves through judgment by sheltering them in Christ.</p>",
"24": "<p>The waters flooded the earth for a hundred and fifty days &#8212; the full duration of judgment before God acts to reverse it (8:1). The complete period of judgment is endured before the waters recede. Jesus spends three days in the tomb &#8212; the full duration of the death before resurrection. The pattern of complete endurance of judgment before divine reversal is the theological structure that the Flood establishes and Christ fulfills at the deepest level: the judgment must be completely borne before the new creation begins. &#8220;It is finished&#8221; (John 19:30) signals that the full duration of the curse has been endured.</p>",
},
"8": {
"1": "<p>&#8220;God remembered Noah&#8221; &#8212; divine remembering (<em>zakar</em>) is the pivot on which the Flood narrative turns. In the OT, God's remembering a covenant or a person is not a mental act but an active, covenant-faithful intervention: God remembered Rachel (30:22), remembered Abraham (19:29), remembered his covenant (Exod 2:24; 6:5). The NT presents Christ as the fulfillment of all divine remembering: &#8220;No matter how many promises God has made, they are &#8220;Yes&#8221; in Christ&#8221; (2 Cor 1:20). The remembering of Noah foreshadows God's ultimate covenant faithfulness in sending Christ to fulfill every promise made to every remnant throughout salvation history.</p>",
"2": "<p>The springs of the deep were closed and the rain stopped &#8212; the ending of judgment by the same divine word that began it. This divine termination of the judgment corresponds to the end of Christ's bearing of wrath on the cross: &#8220;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&#8221; (Matt 27:46) gives way to &#8220;It is finished&#8221; (John 19:30), after which the judgment is complete and the new creation process begins. The closing of the springs of the deep is the type of the ending of divine wrath that Christ's completed sacrifice achieves.</p>",
"3": "<p>The waters receded steadily from the earth &#8212; the gradual reversal of judgment after its complete execution. The steady recession of the waters is the type of the new creation's progressive coming: the kingdom of God is like leaven working through dough (Matt 13:33) or like a mustard seed growing (Matt 13:31&#8211;32). The reversal is real from its beginning but takes time to manifest fully. Christ's resurrection begins the new creation (2 Cor 5:17: &#8220;if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come&#8221;) even while the old creation's groaning continues (Rom 8:22&#8211;23).</p>",
"4": "<p>&#8220;The ark came to rest on the mountains of Ararat on the seventeenth day of the seventh month&#8221; &#8212; a specific date. In the pre-Exodus calendar (when the seventh month was the first month of the year), this corresponds to the seventeenth of what later became the first month, Nisan. Three days after the Passover (14th of Nisan) would be the 17th &#8212; the date of Christ's resurrection. Whether the biblical author intends this correspondence is uncertain, but the canonical pattern is remarkable: the ark &#8220;rested&#8221; (<em>nûaḥ</em>, sharing Noah's root name) on the same calendrical date as the resurrection, initiating a new beginning after judgment was complete. The resting of the ark anticipates the rest that Christ's resurrection inaugurates (Heb 4:9&#8211;10).</p>",
"5": "<p>The tops of the mountains became visible on the first day of the tenth month &#8212; the emergence of solid ground, the first signs of restored creation. The appearance of the mountain tops is the first visible evidence of what God declared when he remembered Noah (v1). The first signs of the new creation similarly appear before the full revelation: Christ's resurrection appearances (1 Cor 15:5&#8211;8) are the firstfruits of the resurrection harvest (1 Cor 15:20&#8211;23), the first visible evidence of what God has declared in Christ.</p>",
"6": "<p>After forty days Noah opened the window of the ark &#8212; the forty days connects to the forty-day pattern (see 7:4). After the complete period, Noah acts in faith to discern the state of the new world. The forty-day pattern culminates in Christ's forty days of post-resurrection appearances before the ascension (Acts 1:3: &#8220;he appeared to them over a period of forty days and spoke about the kingdom of God&#8221;). The window opened after forty days corresponds to the open tomb after three days &#8212; the first act that signals the judgment is ended and the new world is accessible.</p>",
"7": "<p>Noah sent out a raven, which kept flying back and forth until the water dried up &#8212; the raven is a carrion bird that feeds on death; it is comfortable in the environment of judgment and does not return with news of life. It functions as a foil for the dove of v8. The dove/Spirit connection that the NT develops is prepared by this contrast: the Spirit who descends as a dove on Christ (Matt 3:16) is not comfortable with death but brings life. The raven's endless circling above a flooded earth suggests the insufficiency of death-feeding systems to announce new creation; only the dove &#8212; the life-seeker &#8212; can bring that news.</p>",
"8": "<p>Then Noah sent out a dove to see if the water had receded &#8212; the dove as the messenger of new creation. The connection to the Spirit at Christ's baptism is strong: &#8220;The Holy Spirit descended on him in bodily form like a dove&#8221; (Luke 3:22; cf. Matt 3:16; Mark 1:10; John 1:32). The dove in Gen 8 seeks a place to rest where life is present; the Spirit at Jesus's baptism rests on him because he is the beginning of the new creation, the one in whom God's purposes find their resting place. Isa 11:2 anticipates the Spirit resting on the Messiah: &#8220;The Spirit of the LORD will rest on him.&#8221;</p>",
"9": "<p>The dove found nowhere to perch and returned to Noah, who reached out his hand and took it back into the ark &#8212; the Spirit finds no resting place in a world still under judgment. The tender image of Noah reaching out his hand to receive the dove connects to Christ as the one who receives and shelters those who return to him. The dove's return is not failure but faithful reconnaissance: it reports what is true. The Spirit's role throughout OT history was similarly to testify and return &#8212; the full resting of the Spirit on God's people awaits the Messiah on whom the Spirit rests permanently (John 1:33: &#8220;the man on whom you see the Spirit come down and remain is the one who will baptize with the Holy Spirit&#8221;).</p>",
"10": "<p>Noah waited seven more days and sent the dove out again &#8212; the patience of waiting through the Sabbath week before life is declared. The seven-day pattern of sacred waiting runs through the OT (Passover, seven days of unleavened bread; Weeks, seven weeks; Tabernacles, seven days). Christ's death on the sixth day (Friday) and resurrection on the first day of the new week recapitulates the creation pattern of completed work followed by new-creation beginning. The seven-day waits in Noah's reconnaissance mark the passage through sacred time toward the announcement of life.</p>",
"11": "<p>The dove returned with a freshly plucked olive leaf in its beak &#8212; the olive leaf as the sign of life's return. The olive tree is the symbol of Israel and of covenant blessing (Rom 11:17&#8211;24: Paul uses the olive tree for Israel and the Gentiles; Zech 4:2&#8211;14 uses two olive trees for the two anointed ones). The olive oil derived from olives is the anointing oil used for kings and priests &#8212; and the word Messiah (<em>mashiach</em>) means &#8220;anointed one.&#8221; The dove bringing an olive leaf is a convergence of the Spirit-symbol and the anointing-symbol, pointing toward the moment when the Spirit anoints the Messiah at his baptism.</p>",
"12": "<p>Noah waited seven more days and sent the dove out; it did not return &#8212; the dove has found a permanent resting place in the new world. The Spirit's permanent resting is the theological goal: in the OT, the Spirit came upon people for specific tasks and sometimes departed (1 Sam 16:14: &#8220;the Spirit of the LORD had departed from Saul&#8221;). Christ receives the Spirit permanently (John 1:33: the Spirit &#8220;remains&#8221; on him), and through him believers receive the Spirit as a permanent seal and deposit (Eph 1:13&#8211;14; 2 Cor 1:22). The dove that does not return signals the permanent new-creation resting of the Spirit in Christ and his people.</p>",
"13": "<p>Noah removed the covering from the ark and saw that the surface of the ground was dry &#8212; the uncovering and seeing of the new creation. Paul uses unveiling language for the gospel: &#8220;Whenever anyone turns to the Lord, the veil is taken away&#8221; (2 Cor 3:16). The covering of the ark removed at the start of the new-creation era corresponds to the veil of blindness removed when one is in Christ. Seeing the dry ground of the new world after the flood judgment corresponds to seeing the new creation that Christ has inaugurated: &#8220;If anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come: the old has gone, the new is here&#8221; (2 Cor 5:17).</p>",
"14": "<p>By the twenty-seventh day of the second month the earth was completely dry &#8212; the new creation is fully established before Noah is called to exit. The completeness of the new beginning before the new life is formally inaugurated corresponds to the resurrection's completeness before the Spirit is given at Pentecost: Christ's resurrection establishes the new creation; Pentecost inaugurates the new community in it. Both the Flood and the resurrection involve a complete transition rather than a partial one.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;Then God said to Noah&#8221; &#8212; the divine word initiates every major phase of the Flood narrative: the command to enter (7:1), the command to exit (here). God's word frames the whole sequence of judgment and salvation. The divine speech initiating new life after judgment is the template for the angelic announcement at the empty tomb: &#8220;He is not here; he has risen&#8221; (Matt 28:6). In both cases, the word comes after the complete execution of judgment and signals the beginning of the new era.</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;Come out of the ark, you and your wife and your sons and their wives&#8221; &#8212; the divine call out of the ark echoes forward to Christ's calling the dead to life. Jesus's command &#8220;Lazarus, come out!&#8221; (John 11:43) uses the same structural move: a divine word calls the preserved person out from the place where they were sheltered through death. The general resurrection will follow the same pattern: &#8220;the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God and those who hear will live&#8221; (John 5:25). Noah's emergence from the ark at God's call is a type of resurrection-life called forth by divine word.</p>",
"17": "<p>&#8220;Bring out every kind of living creature&#8230; so they can multiply on the earth and be fruitful and increase in number on it&#8221; &#8212; the Adamic commission of Gen 1:28 is renewed through Noah for the post-flood world. Christ restates the commission on a new level: &#8220;Therefore go and make disciples of all nations&#8221; (Matt 28:19). The fruitfulness mandate that flows from creation (1:28), through the Flood (9:1, 7), through Abraham (17:6), through Israel is transformed by Christ into the spiritual fruitfulness of the Great Commission: bearing fruit that remains (John 15:16) and filling the earth with disciples rather than offspring.</p>",
"18": "<p>Noah came out, together with his sons and his wife and his sons' wives &#8212; the emergence of the covenant family into the new world. The family unit that was preserved through judgment emerges to inherit the renewed creation. The church is the covenant family preserved through Christ's death and resurrection, emerging into the new creation that he has inaugurated. The image of Noah's family exiting the ark is the type of the redeemed community who inherit the new heaven and new earth (Rev 21:3: &#8220;God's dwelling place is now among the people&#8221;).</p>",
"19": "<p>All the animals and birds and creatures came out of the ark &#8212; the comprehensive exit mirrors the comprehensive entry (7:14). Every kind that was preserved now inherits the new world. The comprehensive scope of new-creation inhabitants mirrors the comprehensive scope of those gathered to Christ: &#8220;After this I looked, and there before me was a great multitude that no one could count, from every nation, tribe, people and language&#8221; (Rev 7:9). The pairs from every kind preserved in the ark are the prototype of the every-nation multitude preserved in Christ.</p>",
"20": "<p>Noah built an altar and sacrificed burnt offerings from clean animals and birds &#8212; the first recorded altar and the first burnt offerings after the Flood. The altar of sacrifice is the central institution of OT worship, pointing toward the cross as the altar on which the final sacrifice was offered. Noah's burnt offerings &#8212; completely consumed by fire, ascending as smoke &#8212; are the most total form of sacrifice, prefiguring Christ who offered himself completely to God (Heb 9:14: &#8220;through the eternal Spirit offered himself unblemished to God&#8221;). The new world begins with sacrifice; the new creation begins with Christ's sacrifice.</p>",
"21": "<p>&#8220;The LORD smelled the pleasing aroma&#8221; &#8212; the pleasing-aroma language (<em>nichoach</em>) runs through the entire sacrificial system (Exod 29:18; Lev 1:9; Num 15:3&#8211;10) as the technical term for a sacrifice God accepts. Paul applies it directly to Christ: &#8220;Christ loved us and gave himself up for us as a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God&#8221; (Eph 5:2). Every burnt offering that God smelled as a pleasing aroma was a partial anticipation of the one sacrifice God would accept fully and finally in Christ. &#8220;Never again will I curse the ground because of humans, even though every inclination of the human heart is evil from childhood&#8221; &#8212; God's grace after the Flood is not conditioned on human improvement but on his own mercy, a pattern fully expressed in the gospel (Rom 5:8: &#8220;while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&#8221;).</p>",
"22": "<p>&#8220;As long as the earth endures, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat, summer and winter, day and night will never cease&#8221; &#8212; God's covenant preservation of creation's rhythms is the platform on which the entire subsequent redemptive history takes place. The seasons that continue provide the structure for the agricultural metaphors that run through Jesus's teaching (the sower, Matt 13:3&#8211;9; the harvest, Matt 9:37&#8211;38; &#8220;the fields are ripe for harvest&#8221;, John 4:35). The seedtime and harvest promise also grounds Paul's resurrection argument: &#8220;What you sow does not come to life unless it dies&#8221; (1 Cor 15:36) &#8212; the seed-to-harvest pattern that God preserves in creation is the biological template for the death-to-resurrection pattern that Christ fulfills.</p>",
},
"9": {
"1": "<p>&#8220;Be fruitful and increase in number and fill the earth&#8221; &#8212; the Adamic mandate of Gen 1:28 is repeated word-for-word after the Flood. The repetition signals that the post-flood world is a new-creation moment, not merely a continuance. Christ fulfills and transforms this mandate through the Great Commission (Matt 28:19: &#8220;go and make disciples of all nations&#8221;). The physical fruitfulness commissioned at creation and re-commissioned after the flood is fulfilled through spiritual multiplication in Christ: his disciples are the seed that falls into the ground and bears much fruit (John 12:24), the laborers who bring in a harvest (Matt 9:37&#8211;38).</p>",
"2": "<p>&#8220;The fear and dread of you will fall on all the beasts of the earth&#8230; they are given into your hands&#8221; &#8212; the dominion mandate of Gen 1:28 is renewed but in a changed mode: where creation's original dominion was one of care and cultivation, the post-fall, post-flood dominion involves fear and dread. Heb 2:8&#8211;9 applies Ps 8's dominion language directly to Christ: &#8220;We do not see everything subject to [humanity], but we see Jesus.&#8221; Christ is the true human who fulfills the dominion mandate without the distortion of fear and violence, ruling through love and sacrifice rather than coercion. The fear-based dominion of 9:2 is the fallen mode; Christ's rule is the restored mode.</p>",
"3": "<p>&#8220;Everything that lives and moves about will be food for you. Just as I gave you the green plants, I now give you everything&#8221; &#8212; the expansion of the food grant (Gen 1:29 gave only plants; now all creatures are permitted) is the first step toward the full dissolution of dietary restrictions that Christ accomplishes. Jesus &#8220;declared all foods clean&#8221; (Mark 7:19); Peter's vision at Joppa (Acts 10:15: &#8220;Do not call anything impure that God has made clean&#8221;) extends the principle to the Gentiles. The trajectory from plants-only to all-creatures-permitted to all-peoples-welcome traces the progressive opening of God's purposes that Christ completes.</p>",
"4": "<p>&#8220;But you must not eat meat that has its lifeblood still in it&#8221; &#8212; the sanctity of blood established here is the foundation for the entire OT atonement system: &#8220;the life of a creature is in the blood, and I have given it to you to make atonement for yourselves on the altar&#8221; (Lev 17:11). The prohibition against consuming blood is the theological premise on which blood-atonement rests: blood is life; life belongs to God; the shedding of blood is a solemn giving of life. Christ's blood is the ultimate fulfillment of this theology: &#8220;The blood of Jesus his Son purifies us from all sin&#8221; (1 John 1:7); &#8220;without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness&#8221; (Heb 9:22).</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;For your lifeblood I will surely demand an accounting&#8230; from each human being, too, I will demand an accounting for the life of another human being&#8221; &#8212; the accounting for blood establishes the divine moral order in which all human life has absolute value and every death requires a reckoning. This divine accounting grounds the NT's teaching on judgment: &#8220;Just as people are destined to die once, and after that to face judgment&#8221; (Heb 9:27). Christ faces the accounting that sinners owe: &#8220;God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement through the shedding of his blood&#8221; (Rom 3:25), satisfying the divine demand for an accounting for human sin.</p>",
"6": "<p>&#8220;Whoever sheds human blood, by humans shall their blood be shed; for in the image of God has God made mankind&#8221; &#8212; the image of God as the foundation of human dignity and the basis of capital accountability. Christ is the perfect image-bearer: &#8220;the image of the invisible God&#8221; (Col 1:15); &#8220;the exact representation of his being&#8221; (Heb 1:3). The crucifixion is therefore the supreme violation of this principle: the only truly innocent image-bearer, the one who most perfectly reflected God, was murdered by those who claimed to uphold God's law. The NT presents Christ's blood as demanding and providing the ultimate atonement: &#8220;God will bring into judgment both the righteous and the wicked&#8221; (Eccl 3:17), but Christ's resurrection vindicates the innocent and opens the way of forgiveness for the guilty.</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;As for you, be fruitful and increase in number; multiply on the earth and increase upon it&#8221; &#8212; the double repetition of the fruitfulness mandate (v1 and now v7) emphasizes its centrality in the post-flood covenant. The Great Commission (Matt 28:19&#8211;20) is the spiritual fulfillment of this mandate through Christ: &#8220;go and make disciples of all nations.&#8221; The disciples multiply not by physical birth alone but by spiritual rebirth &#8212; the multiplication of those who are born again (John 3:3&#8211;8) through Christ into the family of God.</p>",
"8": "<p>God said to Noah and to his sons with him &#8212; the covenant declaration is addressed to the whole household, not to Noah alone. The covenant's household scope (Noah and his sons) anticipates the household covenant structure of the NT: the Abrahamic covenant applied to entire households through circumcision; baptism applied to households (Acts 16:15, 33; 1 Cor 1:16). Christ's new covenant, while requiring individual faith, is proclaimed to households and operates through family and community structures, continuing the covenant-household pattern established here.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;I now establish my covenant with you and with your descendants after you&#8221; &#8212; the Noahic covenant is the first formally named covenant in Scripture. It joins the Abrahamic (15:18; 17:7), Mosaic (Exod 24:8), Davidic (2 Sam 7; Ps 89), and New Covenant (Jer 31:31&#8211;34) in the chain of God's covenant commitments. Heb 13:20 names the new covenant &#8220;the eternal covenant&#8221; established through &#8220;the blood of the eternal covenant&#8221; &#8212; Christ's blood ratifying what all prior covenants pointed toward. The Noahic covenant is the universal platform on which all subsequent specific covenants are built and that Christ's new covenant ultimately fulfills and surpasses.</p>",
"10": "<p>&#8220;With every living creature that was with you&#8230; every living creature on earth&#8221; &#8212; the Noahic covenant's scope is explicitly cosmic: not just humans but every living creature. Paul in Col 1:20 presents Christ's reconciling work as similarly cosmic: &#8220;through him to reconcile to himself all things, whether things on earth or things in heaven, by making peace through his blood, shed on the cross.&#8221; Rom 8:21 sees creation itself freed from its bondage to decay through the children of God's glory. The Noahic covenant's cosmic scope anticipates the cosmic scope of the new creation Christ inaugurates.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;Never again will all life be destroyed by the waters of a flood; never again will there be a flood to destroy the earth&#8221; &#8212; the Noahic covenant's promise is preservation from external judgment. The new covenant extends this: not just preservation from flood judgment but from the judgment of sin itself. Rom 8:1: &#8220;There is therefore now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus.&#8221; The Noahic covenant removes the threat of flood; the new covenant removes the threat of divine condemnation. The Noahic promise is the precedent for the more radical promise of forgiveness and righteousness that Christ achieves.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;This is the sign of the covenant I am making between me and you&#8230; for all generations to come&#8221; &#8212; the rainbow as the covenant sign is the first in a series of covenant signs: circumcision (17:11), Sabbath (Exod 31:13&#8211;17), Passover blood on the doorposts (Exod 12:13), and the Lord's Supper (Luke 22:19&#8211;20: &#8220;this cup is the new covenant in my blood&#8221;). Each sign points forward and backward in the chain of covenants; the Lord's Supper is the final covenant sign, pointing back to the cross and forward to the eschatological feast (Matt 26:29). All the covenant signs are fulfilled in the one they point to.</p>",
"13": "<p>&#8220;I have set my rainbow in the clouds, and it will be the sign of the covenant between me and the earth&#8221; &#8212; the rainbow appears in Revelation around the throne of God (Rev 4:3: &#8220;A rainbow, resembling an emerald, encircled the throne&#8221;) and around the mighty angel (Rev 10:1: &#8220;He was robed in a cloud, with a rainbow above his head&#8221;). Whether the Revelation angel is Christ or not, the rainbow's presence in both passages signals that the covenant faithfulness God signaled to Noah now encircles the divine throne in the heavenly court. The sign of preservation from judgment surrounds the one who executes all judgment (John 5:22) &#8212; covenant mercy and divine judgment held together.</p>",
"14": "<p>&#8220;Whenever I bring clouds over the earth and the rainbow appears in the clouds&#8221; &#8212; the rainbow sign appears within the cloud of judgment (rain clouds), not after it. The mercy appears within the threat, not after the threat is fully past. This pattern characterizes the gospel: Christ's cross is the site of both judgment (God's wrath poured out) and mercy (atonement accomplished). The mercy does not replace the judgment but is displayed within it &#8212; &#8220;God demonstrates his own love for us in this: While we were still sinners, Christ died for us&#8221; (Rom 5:8), a love displayed precisely within the moment of judgment's execution.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;I will remember my covenant between me and you and all living creatures&#8230; Never again will the waters become a flood to destroy all life&#8221; &#8212; divine covenantal remembering is the basis of the promise. As God remembered Noah (8:1) and acted, and as God remembered his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob at the Exodus (Exod 2:24), so the NT presents God as fulfilling all his covenant remembering in Christ. Luke 1:54&#8211;55: &#8220;he has helped his servant Israel, remembering to be merciful to Abraham and his descendants forever.&#8221; The Noahic promise never to flood is one of the remembered commitments; Christ is the one in whom all such remembering reaches its fulfillment.</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;Whenever the rainbow appears in the clouds, I will see it and remember the everlasting covenant between God and all living creatures of every kind on the earth&#8221; &#8212; the covenant is explicitly &#8220;everlasting&#8221; (<em>berit olam</em>). This term marks the Abrahamic covenant (17:7, 13, 19), the Mosaic Sabbath covenant (Exod 31:16), the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 23:5; Ps 89:28), and the new covenant (Isa 55:3; 61:8; Jer 32:40; Heb 13:20: &#8220;the blood of the eternal covenant&#8221;). The everlasting Noahic covenant is subsumed into and surpassed by the everlasting new covenant established through Christ's eternal sacrifice &#8212; the blood that speaks a better word than Abel's (Heb 12:24) and ratifies the covenant that endures forever.</p>",
"17": "<p>&#8220;This is the sign of the covenant I have established between me and all life on the earth&#8221; &#8212; the covenant is reiterated a final time, marking the completeness of God's commitment. The repeated affirmation of the covenant sign corresponds to the repeated institution of the Lord's Supper: &#8220;Do this in remembrance of me&#8221; (1 Cor 11:25) is a regular re-signing and re-sealing of the covenant, just as the rainbow regularly re-signs the Noahic covenant. The new covenant sign is not a natural phenomenon but a liturgical act &#8212; the community actively commemorating what God has accomplished in Christ rather than passively observing a natural sign.</p>",
"18": "<p>The sons of Noah who came out of the ark were Shem, Ham, and Japheth &#8212; the three sons from whom all nations descend (Gen 10). Christ is identified in Luke's genealogy as descending through Shem (Luke 3:36). The Semitic line carries the covenant blessing (v26); through Abraham, a descendant of Shem, all nations will be blessed (12:3). The table of nations in ch.10 is the genealogical framework for understanding the Great Commission's &#8220;all nations&#8221; &#8212; all of them are Shem, Ham, or Japheth's descendants, all within the scope of God's covenant purposes enacted through Christ.</p>",
"19": "<p>From the three sons of Noah came the people who were scattered over the whole earth &#8212; this provides the theological basis for Paul's Areopagus speech: &#8220;From one man he made all the nations, that they should inhabit the whole earth; and he marked out their appointed times in history and the boundaries of their lands&#8221; (Acts 17:26). Paul uses the single-origin of humanity as the argument for the universality of God's offer through Christ. The scattering from Noah's sons corresponds to the gathering through Christ: Pentecost reverses Babel (Acts 2:8&#8211;11: every nation hears in their own language), and the final gathering brings every nation before the throne (Rev 7:9).</p>",
"20": "<p>Noah began to work the soil and he planted a vineyard &#8212; the vine/vineyard motif enters the narrative here as a primary symbol. Israel is consistently compared to a vine or vineyard in the prophets: Isa 5:1&#8211;7 (the song of the vineyard that failed), Ps 80:8&#8211;16 (Israel as a vine transplanted from Egypt). Jesus inherits the vineyard imagery and transforms it: &#8220;I am the true vine, and my Father is the gardener&#8221; (John 15:1) &#8212; where Israel was the failing vine, Christ is the true vine in whom the vine's purpose is finally realized. The vineyard parables (Matt 20:1&#8211;16; 21:28&#8211;32; 21:33&#8211;46) draw on the OT vine imagery that begins here.</p>",
"21": "<p>Noah became drunk and lay uncovered inside his tent &#8212; Noah as the second Adam who falls: the first Adam experienced shame and nakedness in the garden (3:7); Noah experiences the same in his tent. The parallel is deliberate: the flood did not eliminate human sin. The second Adam also falls, showing that external judgment cannot solve the internal problem. Only Christ, the last Adam (1 Cor 15:45), resists the temptation of the garden (Matt 4:1&#8211;11; 26:36&#8211;46) and overcomes what both Adams failed to overcome. Adam and Noah's failures are the backdrop against which Christ's perfect obedience is the sole exception.</p>",
"22": "<p>Ham saw his father's nakedness and told his two brothers outside &#8212; the exposure of a father's nakedness was a serious violation of household honor in the ANE. The covering of nakedness/shame runs as a theological thread: God covered Adam and Eve's nakedness with garments of skin (3:21); Shem and Japheth will cover Noah (v23); Christ covers the shame of his people: &#8220;I counsel you to buy from me white clothes to wear, so you can cover your shameful nakedness&#8221; (Rev 3:18); &#8220;I will greatly rejoice in the LORD&#8230; he has covered me with the robe of righteousness&#8221; (Isa 61:10). The uncovering of shame by Ham is the opposite of what Christ accomplishes.</p>",
"23": "<p>Shem and Japheth took a garment and, walking backward, covered their father's naked body &#8212; the covering of nakedness/shame is a type of the atonement's covering of human sin and shame. The deliberate backward walk to avoid seeing what must be covered corresponds to the gospel's logic: Christ covers sin not by pretending it doesn't exist but by bearing its consequences (taking the shame of crucifixion, Heb 12:2: &#8220;scorning its shame&#8221;) so that those in him are &#8220;clothed with Christ&#8221; (Gal 3:27). The sons who cover their father's shame are acting in the spirit of the one who covers the shame of his people.</p>",
"24": "<p>Noah awoke and found out what his youngest son had done to him &#8212; the revelation of hidden sin at the moment of awakening. This pattern &#8212; sin committed, then revealed &#8212; anticipates the final judgment in which all hidden things are exposed: &#8220;He will bring to light what is hidden in darkness and will expose the motives of the heart&#8221; (1 Cor 4:5); &#8220;There is nothing concealed that will not be disclosed, or hidden that will not be made known&#8221; (Luke 12:2). The awakening of Noah that reveals Ham's sin is a type of the resurrection-judgment in which the risen Christ reveals all things. This verse does not carry deep Christological weight but participates in the judgment-revelation pattern.</p>",
"25": "<p>&#8220;Cursed be Canaan! The lowest of slaves will he be to his brothers&#8221; &#8212; the curse; and the most significant NT application of curse-theology is Gal 3:13: &#8220;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us, for it is written: &#8216;Cursed is everyone who is hung on a pole.&#8217;&#8221; The system of covenant curses (Noahic, Mosaic) that human sin produces finds its resolution in Christ who bears the curse in the place of the cursed. The curse on Canaan historically sets up the land-narrative in which Israel dispossesses Canaanite peoples; theologically, the framework of curse-and-redemption from curse is the structure Christ fulfills.</p>",
"26": "<p>&#8220;Praise be to the LORD, the God of Shem! May Canaan be the slave of Shem&#8221; &#8212; the blessing on Shem is the covenant channel through which Christ comes. Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, David, and ultimately Jesus are all in the Semitic line that runs from Shem. Luke 3:36 traces Christ's genealogy through Shem explicitly. Noah's blessing on Shem is the earliest canonical statement placing the covenant blessing in the lineage that will culminate in the Messiah. The praise &#8220;be to the LORD, the God of Shem&#8221; anticipates the specifically Semitic character of the Abrahamic covenant and the Jewish particularity of the incarnation (John 4:22: &#8220;salvation is from the Jews&#8221;).</p>",
"27": "<p>&#8220;May God extend Japheth's territory; may Japheth live in the tents of Shem, and may Canaan be the slave of Japheth&#8221; &#8212; the inclusion of Japheth in the blessing of Shem's covenant space anticipates Gentile incorporation into Israel's covenant. Paul's great argument in Romans 11:17&#8211;24 is that Gentiles are wild olive branches grafted into the covenant olive tree of Israel. Gal 3:8 says &#8220;the Scripture foresaw that God would justify the Gentiles by faith, and announced the gospel in advance to Abraham.&#8221; The gathering of the nations into the tents of Shem's covenant God is fulfilled when &#8220;in Christ Jesus&#8230; there is neither Jew nor Gentile&#8221; (Gal 3:28).</p>",
"28": "<p>After the flood Noah lived 350 years &#8212; Noah's post-flood lifespan situates the chronological transition from the antediluvian long-lifespan era to the declining post-flood lifespans. The genealogical framework serves the redemptive-historical timeline that culminates in Christ. This verse does not carry direct Christological freight but is part of the chronological skeleton that Luke incorporates into his genealogy of Jesus (Luke 3:36), placing Christ at the end of the long line from Noah.</p>",
"29": "<p>Noah lived a total of 950 years, and then he died &#8212; the death formula closes the final antediluvian patriarch's account. Death remains the universal human condition even after the flood; the solution to death requires more than judgment and preservation. It requires resurrection. Christ is the one who says &#8220;I am the resurrection and the life. The one who believes in me will live, even though they die&#8221; (John 11:25). Noah survived the flood but still died at 950 years, confirming that the Flood did not solve the death problem. Only the resurrection of Christ &#8212; and the resurrection he promises to those in him &#8212; resolves what the Flood could not.</p>",
},
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis', existing)
    print('Genesis 7-9 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
